      <hedline>
        <hl1>Civility in the Courts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Norman Goodman, New York County Clerk and Clerk of the Supreme Court, notes Vera Institute of Justice's survey finding that positive comments about court clerks by jurors far outweigh complaints (Aug 2 Clyde Haberman column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Clyde Haberman's Aug. 2 NYC column about the New York jury system:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Clyde Haberman's Aug. 2 NYC column about the New York jury system:</p>
        <p>Certainly, incivility and rudeness are conditions we can do without. But because of the vastly different conditions since Chief Judge Judith S. Kaye's jury reform, rude clerks in the jury system are no more present than occupational exemptions.</p>
        <p>The Vera Institute of Justice's jury project reported 29 complaints about rude clerks over a period of five years, while during the same period, 220 jurors reported that ''clerks are pleasant and efficient.''</p>
        <p>NORMAN GOODMAN  New York County Clerk and  Clerk of the Supreme Court  New York, Aug. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
